<subSubSection id="0A4A615298188F6308993F743666E4E8" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" type="nomenclatural notes">
<paragraph id="31667BE07EF43F283004A7B762CE9E4D" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Nomenclatural notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3CA0FD510635C594CEA53BEA86F1AC9F" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">
When describing 
<taxonomicName id="7A897F038EF60A57E2AA75CBB14F1333" family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. rufipes" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" rank="species" species="rufipes">
<emphasis id="5A46256B89E3FF240B3AC273908F8C38" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">C. rufipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="8643F4E69E183B304D2BFAA6F73A51E9" author="Seubert, MA" editor="Martius, CFP" journalOrPublisher="3, part 1. Leipzig apud Frid. Fleischer, Munich" pageId="12" pageNumber="71" pagination="233 - 270" refId="B29" refString="Seubert, MA, 1855. Commelinaceae. In: Martius, CFP, Eichler, AW, Eds., Flora Brasiliensis, vol. 3, part 1. Leipzig apud Frid. Fleischer, Munich: 233 - 270" title="Commelinaceae." volumeTitle="Flora Brasiliensis, vol." year="1855">Seubert (1855)</bibRefCitation>
only mentions that his new species was based on a Martius specimen, at M. After searching the M collection, we found just two specimens from this collector - 
<emphasis id="6EECB5DB6027ED1E01B7B7544D549DF3" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Martius 76</emphasis>
(M0210921) and 
<emphasis id="976B3C0E1E219132DF23945AC6E34180" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Martius 77</emphasis>
(M0210920). Since the specimen 
<emphasis id="438C19C6EB8127DC3EE0EC58B1DF76BA" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Martius 76</emphasis>
was clearly annotated in 
<normalizedToken id="8E2CCE472B35E78EA1C9840311C061FA" originalValue="Seubert’s">Seubert's</normalizedToken>
handwriting it is the obvious choice for a lectotype. Nonetheless, 
<normalizedToken id="B4887501B98D951D05D3546B1F6CA645" originalValue="Seubert’s">Seubert's</normalizedToken>
original description makes it clear that all available specimens had few if any flowers, which matches the specimens found by us at M. This has caused great taxonomic problems over the years, with this name being ascribed to a number of different genera (
<emphasis id="7175127B3FB1321CDC7400A616AB04E3" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">i.e. Athyrocarpus</emphasis>
Schltdl., 
<taxonomicName id="653F9407FA356CC1487D56DEF0C0E504" class="Liliopsida" family="Pontederiaceae" genus="Commelina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Commelina" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8494353559FD32A84020E5B2A3547298" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Commelina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="56A03FA27B8C48261F86BF9BEACB4C3E" authority="Pichon, 1946" authorityName="Pichon" authorityYear="1946" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Commelinopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Commelinopsis" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A1146338F9C315C13AA210F4F815FC3C" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Commelinopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Pichon, and 
<taxonomicName id="C1551452BF1E9B795BD7A9850059962C" authorityName="Hasskarl" authorityYear="1866" class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Phaeosphaerion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Phaeosphaerion" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B8202CFAA492256F478957310FB0BFA0" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Phaeosphaerion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hassk.), and as either accepted or as a synonym by different authors (Faden &amp; Hunt 1987). Thus, in accordance to the 
<emphasis id="9B3EDDB380D1BB81C587A3BBF55D2510" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Code</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="541E78F29500AD520EFCC55D4E2FAD24" author="McNeill, J" journalOrPublisher="International Journal of Botany" pageId="12" pageNumber="71" refId="B21" refString="McNeill, J, Barrie, FR, Buck, WR, Demoulin, V, Greuter, W, Hawksworth, DL, Herendeen, PS, Knapp, S, Marhold, K, Prado, J, Prud'Homme Van Reine, WF, Smith, GF, Wiersema, JH, Turland, NJ, 2012. (2012) International Code of Botanical Nomenclature (Melbourne Code). Adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011. Regnum Vegetabile 154. A.R.G. Gantner Verlag KG, 1-240." title="(2012) International Code of Botanical Nomenclature (Melbourne Code). Adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011. Regnum Vegetabile 154. A. R. G. Gantner Verlag KG, 1 - 240." year="2012">McNeill et al., 2012</bibRefCitation>
, Art. 9.8), we also designate a well-preserved flowering specimen as an epitype, to avoid further taxonomic and nomenclatural problems.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6B9EEA6C28D3656E5E1D43B254A99D05" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" type="taxonomical notes">
<paragraph id="0C16B63945878995F474C031D17303C7" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Taxonomical notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9600DDBFA55CC0A25562D47F2FEC56BC" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">
Apart from the obvious difference in indumenta, the leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="D6467503CC840E6A2AEA3B711CF10E25" authority="var. rufipes" family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. rufipes subsp. var. var. rufipes" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" rank="variety" species="rufipes" subSpecies="var." variety="rufipes">C. rufipes var. rufipes</taxonomicName>
tend to be thinner (lanceolate to elliptic-lanceolate), with a cuneate base and acute apex, while the leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="91F5641162D4DA0D927AD1A9E2A2381E" family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. rufipes subsp. var. var. glabrata" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" rank="variety" species="rufipes" subSpecies="var." variety="glabrata">C. rufipes var. glabrata</taxonomicName>
tend to be wider (ovate-elliptic to ovate), with a round to obtuse base and acuminate apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
